    {
        "type": "highlight",
        "timestamp": "2024-10-19T18:21:14.668Z",
        "text": "The sneezing process is triggered by a gene and a small compound in our nasal cavity. The sneeze signal is processed by the hippocampus in our brain. Sneezing serves as a protective mechanism, flushing out old cells and aiding the immune system in protecting from viruses.\n\nThe speed of a sneeze is determined by reflexive muscle contractions. However, holding back a sneeze may damage the surface of the nose and sinus. For a quieter sneeze, keeping the mouth closed is most effective.\n\nThe sound of a sneeze can be influenced by various factors including cultural norms, psychological factors, and societal norms. For instance, a research by Sheena Cruikshank indicates how these factors can shape the way we sneeze.",
        "highlightedTextLength": 718,
        "timestamp_second": 230.034,
